Using `isRunning` to toggle between a skeleton and actual content is a polished UX pattern. The skeleton uses Tailwind's `animate-pulse` class with gray placeholder divs to mimic the structure of the real content. When the task completes, the skeleton disappears and real data appears seamlessly.

```gjs
// services/cricket-data.js
import Service from '@ember/service'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class CricketDataService extends Service {
  @tracked currentMatch = null
  @tracked isMatchLoaded = false

  fetchCurrentMatch = task({ drop: true }, async (matchId) => {
    const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}`)
    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`Failed to fetch match ${matchId}`)
    }
    this.currentMatch = await response.json()
    this.isMatchLoaded = true
    return this.currentMatch
  })

  clearMatch = () => {
    this.currentMatch = null
    this.isMatchLoaded = false
    this.fetchCurrentMatch.cancelAll()
  }
}
```
Tasks work identically in Services as they do in Components — they are defined as class fields using `task()`. Services with tasks are ideal for shared async operations that multiple components need to access, like fetching the current match or managing authentication state. The task's state (`isRunning`, `last.value`) is shared across all consumers of the service.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { service } from '@ember/service'

export default class MatchViewerComponent extends Component {
