Mutating a `@tracked` step variable between `await` points gives the user real-time progress feedback. Since Glimmer re-renders after each tracked mutation, each step update reflects immediately in the UI. This is simpler than a progress percentage and works well for tasks with a known, fixed number of stages.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

const chunkArray = (array, size) =>
  Array.from({ length: Math.ceil(array.length / size) }, (_, i) =>
    array.slice(i * size, i * size + size)
  )

export default class BatchScoreFetcher extends Component {
  @tracked processed = 0
  @tracked total = 0

  processMatchesInBatches = task(async () => {
    const matchIds = this.args.matchIds
    this.total = matchIds.length
    this.processed = 0

    const chunks = chunkArray(matchIds, 10)
    for (const chunk of chunks) {
      await Promise.all(
        chunk.map(async (id) => {
          const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${id}/score`)
          if (res.ok) await res.json() // process each score
        })
      )
      this.processed += chunk.length
    }
  })

  <template>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" (fn this.processMatchesInBatches.perform)}}>
      Process All Matches
    </button>
    {{#if this.processMatchesInBatches.isRunning}}
      <p>{{this.processed}} / {{this.total}} processed</p>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
Chunking prevents overwhelming the server with hundreds of simultaneous requests. Each chunk of 10 runs in parallel (via `Promise.all`), and chunks execute sequentially via the `for...of` loop. The `@tracked processed` counter updates after each chunk, giving the user a progress indicator.

